article.description: Ukari Figgs had 16 points and Kristin Folkl had 12 points and 11 rebounds as Portland snapped a three-game losing streak by defeating the Orlando Miracle 64-57 Wednesday night, ending their four-game winning streak.
article.headline: Fire's defense shuts the door on Miracle
article.linkText: Fire's defense shuts the door on Miracle
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. -- On a night when Ukari Figgs tied a season high in points and DeMya Walker and Kristin Folkl each had double-doubles, the Portland Fire's most important player might have been someone who scored two points and had one rebound.

Figgs had 16 points and Folkl had 12 points and 11 rebounds as Portland snapped a three-game losing streak by defeating the Orlando Miracle 64-57 Wednesday night, ending their four-game winning streak.

But it was Stacey Thomas' defensive effort on Nykesha Sales that
set the tone for the Fire's first win over an opponent with a
winning record. Sales, the WNBA's player of the week was coming off
a career-high 29 points Sunday. With Thomas guarding her, she
scored just three points and shot 1-for-11.

"Nobody ever talks about Stacey,'' Portland coach Linda
Hargrove said. "That's what Stacey does -- she does all the dirty
work, all the stuff nobody wants to talk about.''

Thomas was making her second start of the season as Hargrove
juggled her starting lineup to create better defensive matchups.
Guard Tully Bevilaqua made her first start of the year as regular
starters Sylvia Crawley and Tamicha Jackson sat down.

The result was one of Portland's best defensive efforts of the
season. The Fire held the Miracle to 28.9 percent shooting and a
43-29 rebounding advantage.

"That's our identity,'' Walker said. "That's been our identity
from the first time we stepped on the floor to become the Portland
Fire. Our identity has been to play with passion, play with heart
and play with aggressiveness.''

Walker had a career-high 14 rebounds to go along with 10 points
for the Fire (5-8.

Shannon Johnson scored 18 points for the Miracle.

Orlando (7-4) lost on the road for the first time in five games.
Elaine Powell, Taj McWilliams-Franklin and Clarisse Machanguana
each scored 10 points in the loss.

"We had a bad offensive night,'' Sales said. "They had a lot
of offensive rebounds, they had a lot of energy.''

Portland's only negative was turnovers -- 22 that resulted in 25
Miracle points. But down the stretch the Fire stopped giving
Orlando extra opportunities. The Miracle took 23 more shot than
Portland, despite being outrebounded.

"Their defense was so aggressive,'' Hargrove said. "We had
very little looks to get somebody posted up inside.''

The Fire looked instead to their perimeter players who turned in
one of their better shooting performances, 41.5 percent.

"We were able to get baskets off the dribble, so DeMya becomes
much more effective,'' Hargrove said.

	   As was Figgs, who was 5-of-7 on the night.

"Our offense was more effective today, really attacked their
defense,'' Figgs said. "They have some very quick guards, and
Shannon Johnson is one of the quickest guards in the league.''
